1
00:00:06,202 --> 00:00:08,884
First of all, thanks a lot for coming along to my talk.

2
00:00:08,884 --> 00:00:10,865
Thanks once again to Lee Petty for the opportunity

3
00:00:10,865 --> 00:00:12,747
to come here and speak at GDC,

4
00:00:12,747 --> 00:00:16,330
talk about some stuff that I've learned.

5
00:00:16,330 --> 00:00:20,233
Don't forget to fill out the questionnaire at the end

6
00:00:20,233 --> 00:00:23,316
and remember to silence your phones.

7
00:00:23,316 --> 00:00:27,119
Okay, so just over two years ago, I got into photography

8
00:00:27,119 --> 00:00:29,061
and that journey has been something that,

9
00:00:29,061 --> 00:00:31,142
it's been like one of the biggest learning experiences

10
00:00:31,142 --> 00:00:31,383
for me.

11
00:00:32,384 --> 00:00:34,485
one to help me kind of grow as an artist,

12
00:00:34,485 --> 00:00:36,545
one to help me get out of my comfort zone.

13
00:00:36,545 --> 00:00:40,467
And in that process, I learned about art,

14
00:00:40,467 --> 00:00:42,968
about art direction, the technical side,

15
00:00:42,968 --> 00:00:44,788
and also things like marketing.

16
00:00:44,788 --> 00:00:47,289
And I really became curious how far I could push that.

17
00:00:47,289 --> 00:00:49,450
And that's kind of what I'm gonna talk about today.

18
00:00:49,450 --> 00:00:51,971
When I think back to when I was a kid,

19
00:00:51,971 --> 00:00:54,311
I was 10 years old, and I really wanted to be a game designer.

20
00:00:55,668 --> 00:00:57,909
and my favorite game was Commandos Behind Enemy Lines

21
00:00:57,909 --> 00:00:59,050
and I wanted to work for Eidos,

22
00:00:59,050 --> 00:01:00,610
I would have killed someone for a job there.

23
00:01:00,610 --> 00:01:02,871
I wanted to live on the moon

24
00:01:02,871 --> 00:01:05,472
and I think I had like at least have a futuristic sports car

25
00:01:05,472 --> 00:01:07,452
which is pretty ambitious.

26
00:01:07,452 --> 00:01:11,714
But by 18, like that dream was just gone and dead

27
00:01:11,714 --> 00:01:15,095
and I really didn't know what I wanted to do.

28
00:01:15,095 --> 00:01:16,335
So I had this kind of high school report

29
00:01:16,335 --> 00:01:19,056
that basically said I was struggling in class

30
00:01:19,056 --> 00:01:21,297
and like I was just super quiet.

31
00:01:23,262 --> 00:01:25,864
And so I took a year after high school

32
00:01:25,864 --> 00:01:27,666
because I really didn't know what I wanted to do.

33
00:01:27,666 --> 00:01:28,466
I felt kind of lost,

34
00:01:28,466 --> 00:01:31,469
and it turned to video games as a way to escape.

35
00:01:31,469 --> 00:01:33,510
And so I played like so much World of Warcraft,

36
00:01:33,510 --> 00:01:36,793
and it really helped build my confidence in a weird way.

37
00:01:36,793 --> 00:01:42,577
It taught me about communication, teamwork, and leadership.

38
00:01:42,577 --> 00:01:44,519
And I would lead, my words,

39
00:01:44,519 --> 00:01:48,121
I would lead raids of like 40 people

40
00:01:48,121 --> 00:01:49,923
and sitting in my bedroom when in reality

41
00:01:49,923 --> 00:01:51,584
I couldn't even talk to someone face to face.

42
00:01:52,827 --> 00:01:54,187
So slowly over that year that I took out,

43
00:01:54,187 --> 00:01:55,168
it helped me build my confidence.

44
00:01:55,168 --> 00:01:57,268
And since then, and even now,

45
00:01:57,268 --> 00:01:59,668
these are the three things that have helped me

46
00:01:59,668 --> 00:02:00,629
get out of my comfort zone.

47
00:02:00,629 --> 00:02:03,749
The first is learning something new.

48
00:02:03,749 --> 00:02:05,329
The second is putting myself out there.

49
00:02:05,329 --> 00:02:08,310
And the third point is surrounding myself with talent.

50
00:02:08,310 --> 00:02:11,671
And these are the things that helped me

51
00:02:11,671 --> 00:02:13,391
land my job at Ubisoft.

52
00:02:13,391 --> 00:02:17,512
And when I joined, I was the youngest director, age 25.

53
00:02:17,512 --> 00:02:19,592
And what I focus on in my day job is visual identity.

54
00:02:20,444 --> 00:02:23,605
So my job is to kind of interpret what game is

55
00:02:23,605 --> 00:02:25,326
and translate that into visuals

56
00:02:25,326 --> 00:02:27,767
so that they're unique, memorable, identifiable.

57
00:02:27,767 --> 00:02:31,088
So essentially branding the games,

58
00:02:31,088 --> 00:02:33,009
creating the logos, motion graphics,

59
00:02:33,009 --> 00:02:33,829
anything that relates to the style.

60
00:02:33,829 --> 00:02:36,630
And so I knew that at the time,

61
00:02:36,630 --> 00:02:40,912
like throughout my career in the kind of year by year,

62
00:02:40,912 --> 00:02:42,713
I've just slowly been trying to push myself

63
00:02:42,713 --> 00:02:44,133
out of my comfort zone.

64
00:02:44,133 --> 00:02:45,213
This is my third GDC talk.

65
00:02:45,213 --> 00:02:47,374
And to do that, I knew I had to like

66
00:02:47,374 --> 00:02:48,335
put myself in the deep end.

67
00:02:49,710 --> 00:02:51,870
And when we learn something new,

68
00:02:51,870 --> 00:02:52,951
it's incredibly daunting.

69
00:02:52,951 --> 00:02:56,091
We don't know anything when we start.

70
00:02:56,091 --> 00:02:57,512
And it's, sorry one sec,

71
00:02:57,512 --> 00:03:03,774
artistically, creatively, we try and think of things

72
00:03:03,774 --> 00:03:04,814
that can help push us forward.

73
00:03:04,814 --> 00:03:07,215
So for me, that one thing that I'll talk about today

74
00:03:07,215 --> 00:03:07,795
is my photography.

75
00:03:09,902 --> 00:03:13,065
So believe it or not, these are actually the first photographs I ever shared online.

76
00:03:13,065 --> 00:03:16,508
It was kind of funny because it's the thing I love about photography.

77
00:03:16,508 --> 00:03:21,113
We take pictures of stuff we care about. I just happen to love dogs.

78
00:03:21,113 --> 00:03:25,477
And when I started taking pictures on my iPhone and when I started to travel,

79
00:03:25,477 --> 00:03:28,100
I moved from Scotland, then to England, and then to Canada.

80
00:03:29,088 --> 00:03:33,190
I would start to travel a lot and I never really left my hometown.

81
00:03:33,190 --> 00:03:34,651
So I started to just take pictures on my iPhone.

82
00:03:34,651 --> 00:03:38,092
Never really shared them and I kept a private Instagram where I think

83
00:03:38,092 --> 00:03:39,933
I had like 10 people, I think one of them's here.

84
00:03:39,933 --> 00:03:44,515
So a very small audience and that's because I just felt this fear,

85
00:03:44,515 --> 00:03:47,116
these anxieties of like, well you know,

86
00:03:47,116 --> 00:03:49,517
they're not like great photos, they're not anything special.

87
00:03:49,517 --> 00:03:52,798
And, but I was like, spending my life

88
00:03:52,798 --> 00:03:55,819
and enjoying it. And so everywhere I'd go,

89
00:03:55,819 --> 00:03:58,640
the biggest learning experience was understanding.

90
00:03:59,856 --> 00:04:03,037
how the architecture, just how the cities in general

91
00:04:03,037 --> 00:04:06,518
had like different moods and different vibes.

92
00:04:06,518 --> 00:04:10,138
So I'd go to places like LA for E3, do press stuff.

93
00:04:10,138 --> 00:04:11,979
And yeah, just a huge, important learning experience.

94
00:04:11,979 --> 00:04:14,699
And as I got more and more into learning stuff,

95
00:04:14,699 --> 00:04:18,880
all of my shots on my iPhone,

96
00:04:18,880 --> 00:04:20,561
I would just take my iPhone everywhere

97
00:04:20,561 --> 00:04:22,201
and every day I would just start taking pictures.

98
00:04:22,201 --> 00:04:23,562
And the more and more I learned,

99
00:04:23,562 --> 00:04:25,862
the more and more I wanted to get better at it.

100
00:04:26,717 --> 00:04:29,899
So I started to think about composition, symmetry,

101
00:04:29,899 --> 00:04:32,521
just trying to find nice visual shapes in architecture

102
00:04:32,521 --> 00:04:33,862
or things that I'd seen.

103
00:04:33,862 --> 00:04:36,404
And I just got really addicted to it.

104
00:04:36,404 --> 00:04:39,947
But at some point I hit a plateau,

105
00:04:39,947 --> 00:04:43,790
because I'm an iPhone and I can only ever take a picture

106
00:04:43,790 --> 00:04:46,652
of what's in front of me.

107
00:04:46,652 --> 00:04:48,234
And I wanted to push that further,

108
00:04:48,234 --> 00:04:50,115
so I ended up leveling up.

109
00:04:52,023 --> 00:04:54,686
And so after I finished up a game at work,

110
00:04:54,686 --> 00:04:58,429
I saved up for a little vacation to Tokyo.

111
00:04:58,429 --> 00:05:01,392
And I bought myself a DSLR because I found myself

112
00:05:01,392 --> 00:05:03,314
getting more serious about what I wanted to learn

113
00:05:03,314 --> 00:05:04,836
and maybe the artistic stuff

114
00:05:04,836 --> 00:05:06,157
that I could learn along the way.

115
00:05:06,157 --> 00:05:07,678
That's where I was like, you know,

116
00:05:07,678 --> 00:05:09,200
how far can I really push this?

117
00:05:09,200 --> 00:05:11,322
And in the end, like I learned so much

118
00:05:11,322 --> 00:05:12,763
about just art direction in general.

119
00:05:14,467 --> 00:05:16,409
One of the first learnings I thought was,

120
00:05:16,409 --> 00:05:18,012
when I think back to when I was a kid,

121
00:05:18,012 --> 00:05:20,175
I just, I would freeze up when people were behind me

122
00:05:20,175 --> 00:05:20,775
when I was drawing.

123
00:05:20,775 --> 00:05:22,378
When I was at university,

124
00:05:22,378 --> 00:05:24,180
I would just like minimize all of my windows

125
00:05:24,180 --> 00:05:26,283
because I was ashamed of the art that I was creating.

126
00:05:26,283 --> 00:05:28,987
And it was really photography that pulled me out of that.

127
00:05:29,933 --> 00:05:32,255
So the question I would ask is,

128
00:05:32,255 --> 00:05:33,995
we spend so much time on our art,

129
00:05:33,995 --> 00:05:36,117
whether it's a game or maybe it's your music,

130
00:05:36,117 --> 00:05:39,478
any of this stuff, and how much time do we actually spend

131
00:05:39,478 --> 00:05:40,639
making sure that people see it?

132
00:05:40,639 --> 00:05:42,720
Because to me, at the end of the day,

133
00:05:42,720 --> 00:05:45,261
it's about creating art that connects with people,

134
00:05:45,261 --> 00:05:47,902
and we get to share our vision and the stuff we care about.

135
00:05:47,902 --> 00:05:52,304
And it wasn't really until I captured this one image that I...

136
00:05:53,867 --> 00:05:55,748
my mentality changed, because every picture

137
00:05:55,748 --> 00:05:58,190
that I'd taken before was merely just like

138
00:05:58,190 --> 00:06:00,852
documenting places I'd seen, stuff I'd ate,

139
00:06:00,852 --> 00:06:04,034
dogs that I saw, and I put this on my personal Facebook

140
00:06:04,034 --> 00:06:06,496
account, and I had like, I don't know how many friends,

141
00:06:06,496 --> 00:06:09,137
a hundred friends, five of them were like,

142
00:06:09,137 --> 00:06:10,458
hey, that's a pretty cool shot,

143
00:06:10,458 --> 00:06:12,460
you should take more pictures, and it really helped me

144
00:06:12,460 --> 00:06:14,841
like, break out of that comfort zone.

145
00:06:16,212 --> 00:06:18,714
And so from there it was like, it's a real turning point.

146
00:06:18,714 --> 00:06:21,036
So there's this taxi driver in Shinjuku in Tokyo,

147
00:06:21,036 --> 00:06:22,978
just happened to take the picture,

148
00:06:22,978 --> 00:06:25,280
the composition's there,

149
00:06:25,280 --> 00:06:28,323
the guy's face just happens to be lit correctly,

150
00:06:28,323 --> 00:06:29,304
and I was like, you know what,

151
00:06:29,304 --> 00:06:32,146
I'm gonna go out every day after that, every night,

152
00:06:32,146 --> 00:06:33,247
and try and find these moments.

153
00:06:33,247 --> 00:06:36,410
And so each day I had left of my vacation,

154
00:06:36,410 --> 00:06:38,011
I just went out and I took different pictures

155
00:06:38,011 --> 00:06:41,114
and I would post them on my Facebook.

156
00:06:41,114 --> 00:06:42,315
And at some point I started to think like,

157
00:06:42,315 --> 00:06:43,156
oh, okay, maybe I can...

158
00:06:43,927 --> 00:06:46,390
branch out a little bit, go a bit further

159
00:06:46,390 --> 00:06:48,572
out of my comfort zone.

160
00:06:48,572 --> 00:06:51,474
All the while, like, realizing that I was taking pictures

161
00:06:51,474 --> 00:06:53,076
of stuff like signage, typography,

162
00:06:53,076 --> 00:06:55,298
the stuff that I was used to dealing with

163
00:06:55,298 --> 00:06:56,379
on a day-to-day basis.

164
00:06:56,379 --> 00:07:00,162
And then, this image stood out in particular,

165
00:07:00,162 --> 00:07:03,565
and I sent it off to Smithsonian's Photo Competition,

166
00:07:03,565 --> 00:07:05,047
and it became a finalist, 2016.

167
00:07:06,719 --> 00:07:08,440
And so two years on, when I look back at this image,

168
00:07:08,440 --> 00:07:09,700
all I can see are the flaws.

169
00:07:09,700 --> 00:07:11,021
So it's that idea of progress.

170
00:07:11,021 --> 00:07:12,841
You know, I go from just taking regular pictures

171
00:07:12,841 --> 00:07:16,082
to suddenly, like, ah, photography's really something

172
00:07:16,082 --> 00:07:18,123
that's driving me.

173
00:07:18,123 --> 00:07:19,804
The funny thing is, I shot this picture in auto

174
00:07:19,804 --> 00:07:22,625
because I didn't know how to use my camera,

175
00:07:22,625 --> 00:07:24,725
even though it was a pretty good DSLR.

176
00:07:24,725 --> 00:07:27,326
And I shot the image in JPEG instead of RAW

177
00:07:27,326 --> 00:07:28,967
because I really didn't know my camera.

178
00:07:28,967 --> 00:07:31,208
I literally got it the week before.

179
00:07:31,208 --> 00:07:33,728
The man's out of focus, there's blurring in the image,

180
00:07:33,728 --> 00:07:35,509
the composition's slightly off.

181
00:07:37,246 --> 00:07:41,350
And it was actually, my first GDC talk was March,

182
00:07:41,350 --> 00:07:43,313
so like 2016, and I just came back,

183
00:07:43,313 --> 00:07:46,055
I did my first talk, and I felt kind of like,

184
00:07:46,055 --> 00:07:47,397
I don't know, like a little bit of a buzz,

185
00:07:47,397 --> 00:07:48,418
and so I was like, you know what,

186
00:07:48,418 --> 00:07:49,439
I'm gonna put my work out there,

187
00:07:49,439 --> 00:07:50,720
because I spoke to people randomly.

188
00:07:50,720 --> 00:07:52,843
At this point, no one had seen my stuff,

189
00:07:52,843 --> 00:07:55,305
and so I sent it off to Kotaku,

190
00:07:55,305 --> 00:07:57,528
just because people encouraged me to do that.

191
00:07:58,752 --> 00:08:00,493
And one of the biggest learnings I think about

192
00:08:00,493 --> 00:08:02,214
in my day job, actually, what I focus on

193
00:08:02,214 --> 00:08:04,916
is really marketing art, or like something

194
00:08:04,916 --> 00:08:06,077
that's gonna summarize what a game is

195
00:08:06,077 --> 00:08:08,938
so people remember it and it's identifiable.

196
00:08:08,938 --> 00:08:11,600
One of the key points I would give off to someone

197
00:08:11,600 --> 00:08:14,002
would be to create a press release.

198
00:08:14,002 --> 00:08:15,222
As artists, developers, whatnot,

199
00:08:15,222 --> 00:08:17,404
we already have this body of work

200
00:08:17,404 --> 00:08:18,564
that we're just kind of sitting on,

201
00:08:18,564 --> 00:08:22,527
and I go into that mentality of just like,

202
00:08:22,527 --> 00:08:23,928
why not just put it out there?

203
00:08:23,928 --> 00:08:26,349
So gather like five or 10 images of the stuff you have,

204
00:08:26,349 --> 00:08:27,710
write a little bio about yourself,

205
00:08:28,512 --> 00:08:32,394
and a little description about what the work is,

206
00:08:32,394 --> 00:08:33,075
and include your links.

207
00:08:33,075 --> 00:08:36,297
Best case scenario, someone is gonna share that,

208
00:08:36,297 --> 00:08:39,158
and it's gonna go further than your own network.

209
00:08:39,158 --> 00:08:40,379
Worst case scenario, nobody replies,

210
00:08:40,379 --> 00:08:42,900
but you already have that work,

211
00:08:42,900 --> 00:08:46,802
so you just send off the email and see where it goes.

212
00:08:46,802 --> 00:08:51,625
And then it went online, and over that period of the year,

213
00:08:51,625 --> 00:08:53,406
went up on all these websites.

214
00:08:54,322 --> 00:08:59,505
Which is crazy because it was just a vacation picture that I took that kind of inspired me to keep taking more and more.

215
00:08:59,505 --> 00:09:08,131
And so at this point, I did my vacation, whatever, went back to my day job and I wanted to get better at photography.

216
00:09:08,131 --> 00:09:15,176
So I started taking photos every day, slowly and surely, learning more about how to operate the camera, learning more about the technical side.

217
00:09:16,268 --> 00:09:18,930
If I was at work, I'd go out on my lunch break

218
00:09:18,930 --> 00:09:20,831
and just go with other people who were photographers.

219
00:09:20,831 --> 00:09:22,993
They would teach me all of the different ins and outs

220
00:09:22,993 --> 00:09:24,634
of how the camera functioned.

221
00:09:24,634 --> 00:09:25,954
On my weekends, I would go out at night

222
00:09:25,954 --> 00:09:27,575
and just practice, practice, practice.

223
00:09:27,575 --> 00:09:28,996
Even when it comes to events like this,

224
00:09:28,996 --> 00:09:30,817
I'll message people and say,

225
00:09:30,817 --> 00:09:33,099
hey, does anyone wanna go take pictures?

226
00:09:33,099 --> 00:09:36,421
So I set myself little mini tasks to make it manageable.

227
00:09:36,421 --> 00:09:39,162
Maybe it was how to capture movement, how to freeze time,

228
00:09:39,162 --> 00:09:40,443
how to get closer to subjects,

229
00:09:40,443 --> 00:09:43,265
because as someone who's kind of awkward,

230
00:09:43,265 --> 00:09:43,725
I just never did it.

231
00:09:45,007 --> 00:09:48,108
And to do that, I knew I needed to level up my gear,

232
00:09:48,108 --> 00:09:50,609
so I reached out to Canon, and they were able to loan me

233
00:09:50,609 --> 00:09:51,650
a bunch of different stuff.

234
00:09:51,650 --> 00:09:55,652
So I thought about the areas I was lacking,

235
00:09:55,652 --> 00:09:57,873
and just so that I could become more comfortable

236
00:09:57,873 --> 00:09:58,774
with those kind of things.

237
00:09:58,774 --> 00:10:02,295
And I keep training my eye, like simple shapes,

238
00:10:02,295 --> 00:10:03,216
symmetry, that kind of thing.

239
00:10:04,252 --> 00:10:06,113
And at some point I realized I had all of this knowledge

240
00:10:06,113 --> 00:10:07,794
that I already had within my comfort zone,

241
00:10:07,794 --> 00:10:10,056
which was directing style guides,

242
00:10:10,056 --> 00:10:11,417
being able to do different styles

243
00:10:11,417 --> 00:10:13,259
for different games or products,

244
00:10:13,259 --> 00:10:15,500
and I wanted to apply that to my photography.

245
00:10:15,500 --> 00:10:18,303
So I looked back at the things I was inspired by,

246
00:10:18,303 --> 00:10:19,964
whether it was Akira, Ghost in the Shell,

247
00:10:19,964 --> 00:10:22,066
Blade Runner, Enter the Void,

248
00:10:22,066 --> 00:10:23,967
and at the time I'd never really seen photography

249
00:10:23,967 --> 00:10:25,548
pushed to that kind of level,

250
00:10:25,548 --> 00:10:28,130
because it was the point where I saw my photography

251
00:10:28,130 --> 00:10:30,312
less like documenting stuff and more like art.

252
00:10:32,203 --> 00:10:35,044
So leaning on my skills in graphic design style guides,

253
00:10:35,044 --> 00:10:38,704
I thought about the use of color, composition, content,

254
00:10:38,704 --> 00:10:41,085
in a way to make it consistent, to be distinctive,

